<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The </FONT><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>Risk
Committee</FONT></B><FONT face=Arial size=2> assists the Board in the oversight
of:</FONT></P>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; TEXT-ALIGN: left" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The Company&#146;s global ERM
      framework;</FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The Company&#146;s capital, liquidity and
      funding planning and strategy;</FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="vertical-align: top; width: 99%; padding-bottom: 4pt">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The major risk exposures of the
      Company, including market, credit, operational, liquidity, model, funding
      and reputational risk, against established risk measurement methodologies
      and the steps management has taken to monitor and control such
      exposures;</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; TEXT-ALIGN: left" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The Company&#146;s risk appetite
      statement, including risk limits and risk tolerance, which are reviewed
      and approved annually and the ongoing alignment of the Risk Appetite
      Statement with the Company&#146;s strategy and capital plans;</FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The Company&#146;s significant risk
      management and risk assessment guidelines and policies;
  and</FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The performance of the CRO, who
      reports to the CEO and the Risk Committee.</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P align=right><FONT face=Arial color=#b3b5b8 size=2>Morgan Stanley 2017 Proxy
Statement&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><FONT face=arial color=#007bc4 size=2>35</FONT></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=left><A href="#toc"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>Table of
Contents</FONT></B></A></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial color=#b3b5b8 size=1>CORPORATE
GOVERNANCE</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>In fulfilling its duties, the Risk
Committee receives reports:</FONT></P>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; TEXT-ALIGN: left" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Regarding the Company&#146;s
      Comprehensive Capital Analysis and Review, Dodd-Frank Act Stress Testing
      and the Company&#146;s Title I Resolution Plan and Recovery
  Plan;</FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>From the CRO, CFO and Corporate
      Treasurer regarding capital, liquidity and funding strategy and planning
      and the major risk exposures of the Company, including market, credit,
      operational, liquidity, model, funding and reputational;</FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>From the Global Audit Director on
      reviews of risk management, liquidity and capital
  functions;</FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Regarding significant strategic
      transactions and investments, new product risk, emerging risks and
      regulated matters relating to its
authority.</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The Risk Committee reports to the entire
Board on a regular basis and the entire Board attends quarterly Risk Committee
meetings and reviews cross-enterprise risks.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The </FONT><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>Audit Committee</FONT></B><FONT face=Arial size=2> assists the Board and
the Risk Committee in the oversight of the major legal and compliance risk
exposures of the Company and the steps management has taken to monitor and
control such exposure, as well as, in coordination with the Risk Committee and
the Operations and Technology Committee, guidelines and policies that govern the
process for risk assessment and risk management.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The </FONT><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>Operations and Technology Committee</FONT></B><FONT face=Arial size=2>
has responsibility for oversight of operations and technology risk, including
information security, cybersecurity (also reviewed with the Board) and
fraud.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The </FONT><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>CMDS
Committee</FONT></B><FONT face=Arial size=2> oversees the Company&#146;s incentive
compensation arrangements to help ensure that such arrangements are consistent
with the safety and soundness of the Company and do not encourage excessive
risk-taking, and are otherwise consistent with applicable related regulatory
rules and guidance.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The committees report to the entire Board
on a regular basis and have overlapping directors, invite Chairs of other
committees to attend meetings, as appropriate given topics of discussion, and
hold joint meetings as necessary to discharge their duties.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The Board has also authorized the
</FONT><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>Firm Risk Committee</FONT></B><FONT face=Arial size=2>, a management committee appointed and chaired by the CEO that includes
the most senior officers of the Company, including the CRO, CLO and CFO, to
oversee the Company&#146;s global ERM framework. The Firm Risk Committee&#146;s
responsibilities include oversight of the Company&#146;s risk management principles,
procedures and limits and the monitoring of capital levels and material market,
credit, operational, model, liquidity, funding, legal, compliance and
reputational risk matters, and other risks, as appropriate, and the steps
management has taken to monitor and manage such risks. The Company&#146;s risk
management is further discussed in Part II, Item 7A of the Company&#146;s Annual
Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December 31, 2016 (2016 Form
10-K).</FONT></P>
<P align=left><B><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt" face=Arial>Assessment of
Leadership Structure and Risk Oversight</FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The Board has determined that its
leadership structure is appropriate for the Company. Mr. Gorman&#146;s role as CEO,
his existing relationship with the Board, his understanding of Morgan Stanley&#146;s
businesses and strategy, and his professional experience and leadership skills
uniquely position him to serve as Chairman and CEO, while the Company&#146;s
Independent Lead Director position enhances the overall independent functioning
of the Board. The Board believes that the combination of the Chairman and CEO,
the Independent Lead Director and the Chairs of the Audit, CMDS, Operations and
Technology, Nominating and Governance and Risk Committees provide the
appropriate leadership to help ensure effective risk oversight by the
Board.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=arial color=#007bc4 size=2>36&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><FONT face=Arial color=#b3b5b8 size=2>Morgan Stanley 2017 Proxy Statement</FONT></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=left><A href="#toc"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>Table of
Contents</FONT></B></A></P>
<P align=right><FONT face=Arial color=#b3b5b8 size=1>CORPORATE
GOVERNANCE</FONT></P>
<TABLE style="LINE-HEIGHT: normal; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 2pt; WIDTH: 100%; BORDER-BOTTOM: #007bc4 1pt solid; TEXT-ALIGN: left" noWrap><B><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt" face=Arial color=#007cc4><A NAME="p37"></A>Compensation Governance and Risk
  Management</FONT></B></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The CMDS Committee actively engages in its
duties and follows procedures intended to ensure excellence in compensation
governance.</FONT></P>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; TEXT-ALIGN: left" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Retains an independent compensation
      consultant and evaluates the independence of such consultant and other
      advisors as required by any applicable law, regulation or listing
      standard. The CMDS Committee&#146;s compensation consultant, Pay Governance,
      assists the CMDS Committee in collecting and evaluating external market
      data regarding executive compensation and performance and advises the CMDS
      Committee on developing trends and best practices in executive
      compensation and equity and incentive plan design. In performing these
      services, Pay Governance met regularly with the CMDS Committee, including
      without management present, and separately with the CMDS Committee Chair.
      Pay Governance does not provide any other services to the Company or its
      executive officers. The Company has affirmatively determined that no
      conflict of interest has arisen in connection with the work of Pay
      Governance as compensation consultant for the CMDS
  Committee.</FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Regularly reviews (i) Company
      performance with respect to execution of long-term strategy and evaluates
      executive performance in light of such achievements; (ii) executive
      compensation strategy, including the competitive environment and the
      design and structure of the Company&#146;s compensation programs to ensure that
      they are consistent with and support our compensation objectives; and
      (iii) market trends and legislative and regulatory developments affecting
      compensation in the U.S. and globally.</FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="vertical-align: top; width: 99%; padding-bottom: 4pt">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Oversees the Company&#146;s incentive
      compensation arrangements to help ensure that such arrangements are
      consistent with the safety and soundness of the Company and do not
      encourage excessive risk-taking, and are otherwise consistent with
      applicable related regulatory rules and guidance. The CRO reviews the
      Company&#146;s incentive compensation arrangements from a risk perspective and
      reports his findings to the CMDS Committee at least annually. The CRO
      concluded that the Company&#146;s current compensation programs for 2016 do not
      incentivize employees to take unnecessary or excessive risk and that such
      programs do not create risks that are reasonably likely to have a material
      adverse effect on the Company.</FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Grants senior executive annual
      incentive compensation after a comprehensive review and evaluation of
      Company, business unit and individual performance for the year, and
      reviews its compensation decisions with our Board for executive officers
      and other senior executives.</FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Together with senior management,
      oversees the Company&#146;s controls regarding the year-end compensation
      process, which have been designed to be consistent with our regulators&#146;
      principles for safety and soundness, including policies and procedures for
      funding and allocating the incentive compensation pool and the use of
      discretion in determining individual incentive compensation awards;
      processes for identifying &#147;risk-taking&#148; employees; and processes to
      administer incentive compensation clawback and cancellation
      features.</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>
<TABLE style="LINE-HEIGHT: normal; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 2pt; WIDTH: 100%; BORDER-BOTTOM: #007bc4 1pt solid; TEXT-ALIGN: left" noWrap><B><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt" face=Arial color=#007cc4><A NAME="p37-1"></A>Director
      Compensation</FONT></B></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The Nominating and Governance Committee
periodically reviews and recommends updates to our director compensation
program, taking into account changes in director responsibilities and market
practice. In 2016, the Nominating and Governance Committee engaged Frederic W.
Cook &amp; Co., Inc. (FW Cook), a compensation consultant, to provide an
analysis of our director compensation program. The Nominating and Governance
Committee evaluated the independence of FW Cook and affirmatively determined
that FW Cook is independent and that FW Cook&#146;s engagement by the Nominating and
Governance Committee would not raise any conflict of interest.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>In August 2016, based on FW Cook&#146;s review
and upon the recommendation of the Nominating and Governance Committee, the
Board amended the Directors&#146; Equity Capital Accumulation Plan (DECAP) to include
an aggregate limit of $750,000 on annual non-employee director compensation,
amended our Corporate Governance Policies to introduce a director equity
ownership requirement of five times the annual cash Board retainer, and approved
changes to the Independent Lead Director, Audit Committee Chair and Risk
Committee Chair fees as described in note 2 to the following table. These
changes enhance the alignment of our non-employee directors&#146; interests with
those of our shareholders. For further information on DECAP, see notes 2 and 3
to the following table.</FONT></P>
<P align=right><FONT face=Arial color=#b3b5b8 size=2>Morgan Stanley 2017 Proxy
Statement&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><FONT face=arial color=#007bc4 size=2>37</FONT></P>

      Independent Lead Director, each of the Board committee chairs and each
      Board committee member receives additional annual retainers for the 2016
      service period, as set forth in the following table. Retainers are
      prorated when a director joins or leaves the Board or a committee at any
      time other than at the annual meeting of shareholders, and no retainers
      are paid if the director is elected to the Board less than 60 days prior
      to the annual meeting. Directors do not receive meeting
  fees.</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>

<P align=right><FONT face=Arial color=#b3b5b8 size=1>CORPORATE
GOVERNANCE</FONT></P>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 7pt" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=1>Messrs. Bowles, Glocer and Traquina
      and Mses. Olayan and Miscik deferred all or a portion of their cash
      retainers into Elective Units or received shares of common stock in lieu
      of cash under DECAP. Elective Units, or shares of common stock, as
      applicable, in lieu of cash retainers earned for the second half of the
      2015 service period were granted in arrears on May 17, 2016, and Elective
      Units in lieu of cash retainers earned for the first half of the 2016
      service period were granted in arrears on November 17, 2016. The number of
      Elective Units granted on May 17, 2016 was based on $26.2455, and the
      number of Elective Units and shares of common stock granted on November
      17, 2016 was based on $39.7101, which, in each case, represents the
      volume-weighted average price of the common stock on the grant
      date.</FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1 color=#007bc4><SUP>(3)</SUP></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 6pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Other than with respect to Mr.
      Nally, represents the aggregate grant date fair value, determined in
      accordance with the applicable accounting guidance for equity-based
      awards, of the annual stock unit award granted on May 17, 2016 for the
      2016 service period. With respect to Mr. Darling, the amount also includes
      the prorated initial stock unit award granted on February 1, 2016 in
      connection with his election to the Board. With respect to Mr. Nally, the
      amount only represents the prorated initial stock unit award granted on
      November 1, 2016 in connection with his election to the Board. The
      aggregate grant date fair value of the stock unit awards is based on the
      volume-weighted average prices of the common stock on the applicable grant
      date as follows: $26.2455 for annual stock units awards; $25.6921 for Mr.
      Darling&#146;s initial stock unit award; and $33.3074 for Mr. Nally&#146;s initial
      stock unit award. For further information on the valuation of these stock
      units, see notes 2 and 18 to the consolidated financial statements
      included in the 2016 Form 10-K.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Under DECAP, directors receive an
      equity award upon initial election to the Board (provided that they are
      elected to the Board no less than 60 days prior to the annual meeting and
      are not initially elected at the annual meeting) and an equity award
      annually thereafter on the date of the annual meeting of shareholders.
      Initial and annual equity awards are granted 50% in the form of stock
      units that do not become payable until the director retires from the Board
      (Career Units) and 50% in the form of stock units payable on the first
      anniversary of grant (Current Units). The grant date fair value of the
      initial equity award is $250,000, prorated for service until the annual
      meeting, and the award is fully vested upon grant. The grant date fair
      value of the annual equity award is $250,000 and the award is subject to
      monthly vesting until the one-year anniversary of the grant date.
      Directors may elect to extend deferral of their Career Units and Current
      Units beyond the scheduled payment date, subject to specified
      limitations.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1 color=#007bc4><SUP>(4)</SUP></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>The following table sets forth
      the aggregate number of shares underlying DECAP stock units outstanding at
      December 31, 2016.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>
<DIV align=center>
<TABLE style="LINE-HEIGHT: 14pt; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="70%" border=0>

  <TR vAlign=bottom>

    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: right; width: 3%; padding-right: 4pt"><B><FONT face=Arial size=1>Stock Units (#)</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: left; width: 96%; padding-left: 4pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>Erskine B. Bowles</FONT></TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: right; width: 3%; padding-right: 4pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>148,315</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: left; width: 96%; padding-left: 4pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>Alistair M. Darling</FONT></TD>

<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial size=2><A href="#toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial color=#b3b5b8 size=1>CORPORATE
GOVERNANCE</FONT></P>
<TABLE style="BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 2pt; BORDER-BOTTOM: #007bc4 1pt solid" noWrap align=left width="100%" bgColor=#ffffff><B><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt" face=Arial color=#007bc4><A NAME="p40"></A>Related Person Transactions
  Policy</FONT></B></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Our Board has adopted a written Related
Person Transactions Policy (Policy) requiring the approval or ratification by
the Nominating and Governance Committee of transactions (including material
amendments or modifications to existing transactions) where the Company is a
participant, the transaction exceeds $120,000 and a related person (directors or
director nominees, executive officers, 5% shareholders and immediate family
members of the foregoing) has a direct or indirect material interest. Under the
Policy, in determining whether to approve or ratify such Related Person
Transactions, the Nominating and Governance Committee considers all relevant
facts and circumstances, including, but not limited to: the terms and commercial
reasonableness of the transaction; the size of the transaction; the materiality
to, and interest of, the related person and the Company in the transaction;
whether the transaction would, or would be perceived to, present an improper
conflict of interest for the related person; and, if the related person is an
independent director, the impact on the director&#146;s independence. Certain
transactions are not subject to the Policy, including compensation of executive
officers approved by the CMDS Committee and ordinary course commercial or
financial services transactions between the Company and an entity in which a
related person has an interest if the transaction is made under terms and
conditions and under circumstances substantially similar to those prevailing at
the time for comparable transactions with unaffiliated third parties and the
related person does not otherwise have a direct or indirect material interest in
the transaction.</FONT></P>
<TABLE style="BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 2pt; BORDER-BOTTOM: #007bc4 1pt solid" noWrap align=left width="100%" bgColor=#ffffff><B><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt" face=Arial color=#007bc4><A NAME="p40-1"></A>Certain
Transactions</FONT></B></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Our subsidiaries may extend credit in the
ordinary course of business to certain of our directors, officers and members of
their immediate families. These extensions of credit may be in connection with
margin loans, mortgage loans or other extensions of credit by our subsidiaries.
These extensions of credit are made in the ordinary course of business, on
substantially the same terms, including interest rates and collateral, as those
prevailing at the time for comparable loans with persons not related to the
lender and do not involve more than the normal risk of collectability or present
other unfavorable features.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Each of MUFG, State Street Corporation
(State Street), T. Rowe Price Associates, Inc. (T. Rowe Price) and BlackRock,
Inc. (BlackRock) beneficially owns 5% or more of the outstanding shares of
Morgan Stanley common stock as reported under &#147;Principal Shareholders.&#148; During
2016, we engaged in transactions in the ordinary course of business with each of
MUFG, State Street, T. Rowe Price and BlackRock and certain of their respective
affiliates, including investment banking, financial advisory, sales and trading,
derivatives, investment management, lending, securitization and other financial
services transactions. Such transactions were on substantially the same terms as
those prevailing at the time for comparable transactions with unrelated third
parties.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>A child of Jeffrey Brodsky, an executive
officer, is a non-executive employee of the Company and received compensation in
2016 of approximately $144,000 and standard benefits applicable to similarly
situated employees. </FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>In addition to the transactions described
above, as part of the global strategic alliance between MUFG and the Company, on
May 1, 2010 the Company and MUFG formed a joint venture in Japan of their
respective investment banking and securities businesses by forming two joint
venture companies. MUFG contributed the investment banking, wholesale and retail
securities businesses conducted in Japan by Mitsubishi UFJ Securities Co., Ltd.
into one of the joint venture entities named Mitsubishi UFJ Morgan Stanley
Securities Co., Ltd. (MUMSS). The Company contributed the investment banking
operations conducted in Japan by its subsidiary, Morgan Stanley MUFG Securities
Co., Ltd. (MSMS), formerly known as Morgan Stanley Japan Securities Co., Ltd.,
into MUMSS (MSMS, together with MUMSS, the Joint Venture). MSMS has continued
its sales and trading and capital markets business conducted in Japan. The
Company owns a 40% economic interest in the Joint Venture and MUFG owns a 60%
economic interest in the Joint Venture. The Company holds a 40% voting interest
and MUFG holds a 60% voting interest in MUMSS, while the Company holds a 51%
voting interest and MUFG holds a 49% voting interest in MSMS. Other initiatives
that are part of the Company&#146;s global strategic alliance with MUFG include a
loan marketing joint venture in the Americas, business referral arrangements in
Asia, Europe, the Middle East and Africa, referral agreements for commodities
transactions and a secondment arrangement of personnel between MUFG and the
Company for the purpose of sharing best practices and expertise.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial color=#007bc4 size=2>40</FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><FONT face=Arial color=#b3b5b8 size=2>Morgan Stanley 2017 Proxy Statement</FONT></P>

      <P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial color=#007bc4>Ratification of
      Appointment of Morgan Stanley&#146;s Independent Auditor</FONT></B></P></TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-RIGHT: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" vAlign=top>&nbsp;</TD></TR>
  <TR>

    <TD></TD>

    <TD vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="font-size: 11pt">Our Board unanimously recommends
      that you vote <FONT color=#007bc4>&#147;FOR&#148;</FONT> the ratification of
      Deloitte &amp; Touche&#146;s appointment as our independent
      auditor.</FONT></B></P></TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-RIGHT: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" vAlign=top>&nbsp;</TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="BORDER-LEFT: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid">&nbsp;</TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 2pt; VERTICAL-ALIGN: top; WIDTH: 1%; BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid">&nbsp;</TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" vAlign=top width="99%">&nbsp;</TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-RIGHT: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" vAlign=top>&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE><BR>

<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The Audit Committee has the sole authority
and responsibility to appoint, compensate, retain, oversee and evaluate the
independent registered public accounting firm retained to audit the Company&#146;s
consolidated financial statements (independent auditor). The Audit Committee
reviews and assesses annually the qualifications and performance of the
independent auditor. The Audit Committee also evaluates whether it is
appropriate to rotate the independent auditor and ensures the mandatory, regular
rotation of the lead audit partner of the independent auditor and, in connection
with such rotation, the Audit Committee is directly involved in the selection of
the lead audit partner, who may provide services to the Company for a maximum of
five consecutive years. As part of the Audit Committee&#146;s annual review of
Deloitte &amp; Touche LLP (Deloitte &amp; Touche), the Audit Committee reviewed
and considered, among other factors:</FONT></P>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; TEXT-ALIGN: left" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2></FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>the
      results of management&#146;s assessment that includes the results of a global
      management survey of overall performance; </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2></FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>Deloitte &amp; Touche&#146;s independence from the Company, noting that
      Deloitte &amp; Touche does not provide any non-audit services to the
      Company other than those deemed permissible, as described under
      &#147;Independent Auditor Fees&#148;; </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="vertical-align: top; width: 99%; padding-bottom: 4pt">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2></FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>the
      professional qualifications of Deloitte &amp; Touche and that of the lead
      audit partner and other key engagement partners; </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2></FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>Deloitte &amp; Touche&#146;s tenure as independent auditor, including
      the controls and processes in place (such as the mandatory rotation of
      audit partners) that help ensure Deloitte &amp; Touche&#146;s continued
      independence from the Company; </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2></FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>Deloitte &amp; Touche succession planning for senior Deloitte &amp;
      Touche personnel on the engagement; </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="vertical-align: top; width: 99%; padding-bottom: 4pt">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2></FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>Deloitte &amp; Touche&#146;s historic and current quality of service,
      including quality of communication and interactions with the Audit
      Committee; </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2></FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>Deloitte &amp; Touche&#146;s global capabilities and expertise in
      handling the breadth of the Company&#146;s global operations and businesses;
      </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2></FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>the
      appropriateness of Deloitte &amp; Touche fees; </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="vertical-align: top; width: 99%; padding-bottom: 4pt">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2></FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>external data on audit quality and performance, including recent
      Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (PCAOB) reports on Deloitte
      &amp; Touche and peer firms; </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2></FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>the
      potential impact and advisability of selecting a different independent
      auditor; and </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2></FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>whether retaining Deloitte &amp; Touche is in the best interest of
      Morgan Stanley and its stockholders.</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Based on this review, the Audit Committee
has appointed Deloitte &amp; Touche as independent auditor for the year ending
December 31, 2017 and presents this selection to the shareholders for
ratification. The Audit Committee believes the continued retention of Deloitte
&amp; Touche is in the best interest of the Company and its shareholders.
Deloitte &amp; Touche was selected as independent auditor upon the merger
creating the current Company in 1997 and has served continuously as independent
auditor since that time. Deloitte &amp; Touche will audit the Company&#146;s
consolidated financial statements included in the Annual Report on Form 10-K for
the year ending December 31, 2017 and will perform other permissible,
pre-approved services. </FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Deloitte &amp; Touche representatives will
attend the annual meeting. They will be available to respond to appropriate
shareholder questions and will have the opportunity to make a statement if they
desire to do so. If shareholders do not ratify the appointment, the Audit
Committee will reconsider it.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>Our Board unanimously recommends that
you vote</FONT></B><B><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#007bc4> &#147;FOR&#148;</FONT></B><B><FONT face=Arial size=2> the ratification of Deloitte &amp; Touche&#146;s appointment as
our independent auditor. Proxies solicited by the Board will be voted
</FONT></B><B><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#007bc4>&#147;FOR&#148;</FONT></B><B><FONT face=Arial size=2> this ratification unless otherwise instructed.</FONT></B></P>
<P align=right><FONT face=Arial color=#b3b5b8 size=2>Morgan Stanley 2017 Proxy
Statement&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><FONT face=Arial color=#007bc4 size=2>41</FONT></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial size=2><A href="#toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial color=#b3b5b8 size=1>AUDIT MATTERS</FONT></P>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="FONT-SIZE: 14pt" color=#007bc4><A NAME="p42"></A>AUDIT COMMITTEE REPORT</FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The Audit Committee&#146;s charter (available
at www.morganstanley.com/about-us-governance) provides that the Audit Committee
is responsible for the oversight of the integrity of the Company&#146;s consolidated
financial statements, the Company&#146;s system of internal control over financial
reporting, certain aspects of the Company&#146;s risk management as described in the
charter, the qualifications and independence of the independent auditor, the
performance of the Company&#146;s internal auditor and independent auditor, and the
Company&#146;s compliance with legal and regulatory requirements. We have the sole
authority and responsibility to appoint, compensate, retain, oversee, evaluate
and, when appropriate, replace the Company&#146;s independent auditor. As described
under &#147;Corporate Governance&#151;Corporate Governance Highlights&#151;Board Meetings and
Committees,&#148; the Board has determined that all members of the Audit Committee
are independent and &#147;financially literate&#148; within the meaning of the NYSE
listing standards and &#147;audit committee financial experts&#148; within the meaning of
SEC rules. </FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The Audit Committee serves in an oversight
capacity and is not part of the Company&#146;s managerial or operational
decision-making process. Management is responsible for the financial reporting
process, including the system of internal controls, for the preparation of
consolidated financial statements in accordance with accounting principles
generally accepted in the U.S. (GAAP) and for the report on the Company&#146;s
internal control over financial reporting. The Company&#146;s independent auditor,
Deloitte &amp; Touche, is responsible for auditing those financial statements
and expressing an opinion as to their conformity with GAAP and expressing an
opinion on the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal control over financial
reporting. Our responsibility is to oversee the financial reporting process and
to review and discuss management&#146;s report on the Company&#146;s internal control over
financial reporting. We rely, without independent verification, on the
information provided to us and on the representations made by management, the
internal auditor and the independent auditor.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The Audit Committee, among other
things:</FONT></P>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; TEXT-ALIGN: left" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Reviewed and discussed the Company&#146;s
      quarterly earnings releases, Quarterly Reports on Form 10-Q and Annual
      Report on Form 10-K, including the consolidated financial statements;
      </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Reviewed the major legal and
      compliance risk exposures and the guidelines and policies that govern the
      process for risk assessment and risk management, including coordinating
      with the Risk Committee and the Operations and Technology Committee;
      </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="vertical-align: top; width: 99%; padding-bottom: 4pt">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Reviewed, discussed and approved the
      plan and scope of the work and coverage of the internal auditor for 2016
      and reviewed and discussed summaries of the significant reports to
      management by the internal auditor; </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Reviewed the functional reporting of
      the Global Audit Director to the Audit Committee, and reviewed the
      performance and compensation as well as independence of the Global Audit
      Director; </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Reviewed and discussed the plan and
      scope of the work of the independent auditor for 2016; </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="vertical-align: top; width: 99%; padding-bottom: 4pt">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Reviewed and discussed reports from
      management on the Company&#146;s policies regarding applicable legal and
      regulatory requirements, and reviewed, discussed and approved the
      Company&#146;s annual compliance plan; </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Met with and received reports from
      senior representatives of the Finance Department, Legal and Compliance
      Division and the Internal Audit Department; and </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Met with Deloitte &amp; Touche, the
      internal auditor and Company management, including the CFO, CLO, Chief
      Compliance Officer and Global Audit Director in executive
      sessions.</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>We reviewed and discussed with management,
the internal auditor and Deloitte &amp; Touche: the audited consolidated
financial statements for 2016, the critical accounting policies that are set
forth in the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form 10-K, management&#146;s annual report on
the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting and Deloitte &amp;
Touche&#146;s opinion on the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal control over
financial reporting.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>We discussed with Deloitte &amp; Touche
matters that independent registered public accounting firms must discuss with
audit committees pursuant to auditing standards adopted by the PCAOB. Deloitte
&amp; Touche also provided to the Audit Committee the written disclosures and
the letter required by applicable requirements of the PCAOB regarding the
independent auditor&#146;s communications with the Audit Committee concerning
independence and represented that it is independent from the Company.
</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>We also discussed with Deloitte &amp;
Touche their independence from the Company, and considered if services they
provided to the Company beyond those rendered in connection with their audit of
the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements, reviews of the Company&#146;s
interim condensed consolidated financial statements included in its Quarterly
Reports on Form 10-Q and their opinion on the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s
internal control over financial reporting were compatible </FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial color=#007bc4 size=2>42</FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT><FONT face=Arial color=#b3b5b8 size=2>Morgan Stanley 2017 Proxy Statement</FONT></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>

<P align=right><FONT face=Arial color=#b3b5b8 size=1>AUDIT MATTERS</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>with maintaining their independence. We
also reviewed and pre-approved, among other things, the audit, audit-related and
tax services performed by Deloitte &amp; Touche. We received regular updates on
the amount of fees and scope of audit, audit-related and tax services
provided.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Based on our review and the meetings,
discussions and reports discussed above, and subject to the limitations on our
role and responsibilities referred to above and in the Audit Committee charter,
we recommended to the Board that the Company&#146;s audited consolidated financial
statements for 2016 be included in the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form 10-K. We
also selected Deloitte &amp; Touche as the Company&#146;s independent auditor for the
year ending December 31, 2017 and are presenting the selection to the
shareholders for ratification.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Respectfully submitted, <BR><BR>Robert H.
Herz, Chair <BR>Thomas H. Glocer <BR>Dennis M. Nally <BR>Donald T. Nicolaisen
<BR>Perry M. Traquina</FONT></P>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="FONT-SIZE: 14pt" color=#007bc4><A NAME="p43"></A>INDEPENDENT AUDITOR&#146;S
FEES</FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The Audit Committee is responsible for
overseeing the audit fee negotiations associated with the engagement of Deloitte
&amp; Touche. The Audit Committee pre-approves categories of audit and permitted
non-audit services that Deloitte &amp; Touche may perform for the Company and
sets budgeted fee levels for such services. The Company reviews proposed
engagements, in conjunction with Deloitte &amp; Touche, to confirm the proposed
engagements fit within a category of pre-approved services and such engagements
are documented and reported to the Audit Committee on a quarterly basis. Any
proposed service category, engagement or budgeted fee adjustment that has not
been pre-approved by the Audit Committee may be approved by the Audit Committee
chair between regularly scheduled quarterly meetings and reported to the Audit
Committee at its next quarterly meeting. Any fees for services in excess of the
pre-approved budgeted fees must be specifically approved. </FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The following table summarizes the
aggregate fees (including related expenses; $ in millions) for professional
services provided by Deloitte &amp; Touche related to 2016 and 2015.</FONT></P>

<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>As required by Section 14A of the
Securities Exchange Act of 1934, this proposal seeks a shareholder advisory vote
to approve the compensation of our NEOs as disclosed pursuant to Item 402 of
Regulation S-K through the following resolution: </FONT></P>
<P ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="padding-left: 15pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>&#147;RESOLVED, that the Company&#146;s shareholders
approve, on an advisory basis, the compensation of the Company&#146;s named executive
officers, as disclosed in the Company&#146;s proxy statement for the 2017 Annual
Meeting of Shareholders pursuant to the compensation disclosure rules of the
Securities and Exchange Commission (which disclosure includes the Compensation
Discussion and Analysis and the accompanying compensation tables and related
narrative).&#148; </FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Although this &#147;Say on Pay&#148; vote is
advisory and is not binding on our Board, the CMDS Committee will take into
consideration the outcome of the vote when making future executive compensation
decisions. At the 2016 annual meeting of stockholders, approximately 90% of the
votes cast were in favor of our &#147;Say on Pay&#148; proposal. The CMDS Committee
considered our &#147;Say on Pay&#148; result, and, in light of the significant majority of
votes cast in favor of the 2015 compensation of our NEOs, did not materially
change the overall approach for 2016 compensation from the prior year. The 2016
pay decision for the CEO was $22.5 million, a 7% increase from $21 million for
2015, with shareholder-aligned features: 72% deferred over three years and
subject to clawback, with 39% of such deferred compensation delivered through
future performance-vested equity awards. The 2016 pay decision for the CEO was
based on the CMDS Committee&#146;s assessment of Mr. Gorman&#146;s strong individual
performance and Morgan Stanley&#146;s progress in relation to its strategic
objectives, financial performance and shareholder returns.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>As discussed in the CD&amp;A, the Board
believes that our current executive compensation program appropriately links the
compensation of our NEOs to our performance and properly aligns the interests of
our NEOs with those of our shareholders.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>We urge our shareholders to read the
&#147;Overview of Voting Items,&#148; CD&amp;A and &#147;Executive Compensation Tables,&#148; which
provide a detailed description of our executive compensation program.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>Our Board unanimously recommends that
you vote </FONT></B><B><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#007bc4>&#147;FOR&#148;</FONT></B><B><FONT face=Arial size=2> this proposal. Proxies solicited by the Board will be voted
</FONT></B><B><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#007bc4>&#147;FOR&#148;</FONT></B><B><FONT face=Arial size=2> this proposal unless otherwise instructed.</FONT></B></P>

COMPENSATION</FONT></P>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="FONT-SIZE: 14pt" color=#007bc4><A NAME="p45"></A>COMPENSATION DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
(CD&amp;A)</FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>In this CD&amp;A, we review the objectives
and elements of Morgan Stanley&#146;s executive compensation program, its alignment
with Morgan Stanley&#146;s performance and the 2016 compensation decisions for our
named executive officers (NEOs): </FONT></P>
<DIV align=right>
<TABLE style="LINE-HEIGHT: 14pt; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="90%" border=0>

  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="25%"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>James
    Gorman</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="74%"><FONT face=Arial size=2>CEO</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="25%"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>Colm
    Kelleher</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="74%"><FONT face=Arial size=2>President</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="25%"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>Jonathan
      Pruzan</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="74%"><FONT face=Arial size=2>CFO</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="25%"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>James
      Rosenthal</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="74%"><FONT face=Arial size=2>Chief Operating Officer (COO) during
      2016</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="25%"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>Daniel
      Simkowitz</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="74%"><FONT face=Arial size=2>Head of Investment
  Management</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE></DIV><BR>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Effective December 31, 2016, Mr. Rosenthal
ceased to be an executive officer. <BR>
<BR>
The CD&amp;A is comprised of the following
sections: </FONT></P>
<TABLE style="LINE-HEIGHT: 14pt; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-top: #007bc4 1pt solid; border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: left; width: 97%; padding-left: 4pt"></TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-top: #007bc4 1pt solid; border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: right; width: 2%; padding-right: 4pt"><B><FONT face=Arial size=1>Page:</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: left; width: 97%; padding-left: 4pt"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>1. Overview</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: right; width: 2%; padding-right: 4pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>45</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: left; width: 97%; padding-left: 4pt"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>2. Compensation Objectives and Strategy</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: right; width: 2%; padding-right: 4pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>50</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: left; width: 97%; padding-left: 4pt"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>3. Framework for Making Compensation Decisions</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: right; width: 2%; padding-right: 4pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>50</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: left; width: 97%; padding-left: 4pt"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>4. Compensation Decisions and Program</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: right; width: 2%; padding-right: 4pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>54</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: left; width: 97%; padding-left: 4pt"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>5. Notes to the Compensation Discussion and
      Analysis</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: right; width: 2%; padding-right: 4pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>57</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>
<TABLE style="BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 2pt; BORDER-BOTTOM: #007bc4 1pt solid" noWrap align=left width="100%" bgColor=#ffffff><B><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt" face=Arial color=#007bc4>1. Overview</FONT></B></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The CMDS Committee considers multiple
factors in determining executive compensation to ensure that Morgan Stanley&#146;s
compensation program is shareholder-aligned, motivating, and competitive, and
reflects current best practices in corporate governance, risk management, and
regulatory principles. The CMDS Committee takes into consideration progress with
respect to the Company&#146;s long-term strategic plan, as informed by financial and
non-financial goals.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The CMDS Committee, with the advice of its
independent compensation consultant, Pay Governance, places performance at the
forefront of the executive compensation program. This is demonstrated in the
structure of executive compensation and the performance results that drive
compensation decisions for our NEOs. The Committee&#146;s approach to executive pay
is also informed by input from shareholders. Our commitment to this approach is
demonstrated in our CEO pay framework. </FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>As in prior years, the CMDS Committee used
a well-defined process to determine CEO compensation for 2016. </FONT></P>
<TABLE style="BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

      <DIV style="padding-bottom: 4pt;PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; TEXT-INDENT: -14.5pt"><FONT style="PADDING-RIGHT: 8pt; FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>The Board sets annual performance priorities at the
      beginning of each year to guide its assessment of Company and executive
      performance</FONT></DIV>
      <DIV style="PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; TEXT-INDENT: -14.5pt"><FONT style="PADDING-RIGHT: 8pt; FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>The priorities include both financial and non-financial
      performance metrics for the Company and its business
    segments</FONT></DIV></TD>

      performance at year-end, including:</FONT></DIV>
      <DIV style="padding-bottom: 4pt; PADDING-LEFT: 24pt; TEXT-INDENT: -9pt" align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#007bc4>&#150; </FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>Progress in the
      Company&#146;s annual performance priorities</FONT></DIV>
      <DIV style="padding-bottom: 4pt; PADDING-LEFT: 24pt; TEXT-INDENT: -9pt" align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#007bc4>&#150; </FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>Progress in achieving
      the Company&#146;s strategic goals; and</FONT></DIV>
      <DIV style="PADDING-LEFT: 24pt; TEXT-INDENT: -9pt" align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#007bc4>&#150; </FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>The CEO&#146;s overall
      leadership</FONT></DIV></TD>

      year-end based on its assessment of performance and discussion with the
      Board</FONT></DIV></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top width="2%"></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>At 2016 year end, CEO total compensation
was set at $22.5 million for 2016, a 7% increase from $21 million for 2015 and
flat to his 2014 compensation, with shareholder-aligned features: </FONT></P>

    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>72% deferred over three years and
      subject to clawback, </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>

    <TD vAlign=top width="99%">
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>39% of such deferred compensation
      delivered through future performance-vested equity
  awards.</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>

<P STYLE="text-align: left"><FONT face=Arial color=#b3b5b8 size=1>EXECUTIVE
COMPENSATION</FONT></P>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt">1.1. Performance-Based Approach to
Executive Compensation and 2016 Performance Highlights</FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>In its assessment of 2016 performance, the
CMDS Committee considered Morgan Stanley&#146;s progress in relation to its long-term
strategic objectives, financial performance, and shareholder returns.
</FONT></P>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt">Strategic Objectives</FONT></B><B><FONT face=Arial size=2><font color=#007bc4><SUP>(1)(2)</SUP></font></FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>In 2016, the Company continued to
successfully execute on its long-term strategic objectives for 2017, which the
Board oversees. Each year shareholders receive an overview of the Company&#146;s
long-term strategic priorities (including specific objectives) and a summary of
progress on the prior year&#146;s strategic plan. </FONT></P>

<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt">Financial
Performance</FONT></B><B><FONT face=Arial size=2><font color=#007bc4><SUP>(1)(2)</SUP></font></FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The Company delivered improved financial
performance in 2016, driven by disciplined expense management. Pre-tax profit
(PBT)<font color=#007bc4><SUP>(8)</SUP></font> for 2016 grew by 12% on revenues that were essentially flat
from 2015 excluding DVA<font color=#007bc4><SUP>(6)(9)</SUP></font>, and both ROE, ex DVA<font color=#007bc4><SUP>(7)</SUP></font> and
ROE, ex DVA and discrete tax benefits (Operating ROE)<font color=#007bc4><SUP>(10)</SUP></font> were
approximately 8.0%, on a path towards achieving the ROE Target of 9-11% by
2017<font color=#007bc4><SUP>(7)</SUP></font>. </FONT></P>
<TABLE style="BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

      <P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial size=1>2016 Financial Results Summary
      </FONT></B></P></TD></TR>

    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; background-color: #E7EAEF; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt; padding-left: 4pt">

      ($Bn)</FONT></B><B><FONT face=Arial size=1 color=#007bc4><SUP>(9)</SUP></FONT></B></P></TD></TR>

<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial size=2><A href="#toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></B></p>
<P STYLE="text-align: right"><FONT face=Arial size=1 color=#B3B5B8>EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION</FONT></P>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt">Shareholder Returns</FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The Company&#146;s strategic progress and
improved financial performance in 2016 contributed to Morgan Stanley&#146;s improved
share price. Total shareholder return (TSR) was 36% over 2016, 42% over the
three-year period from 2014 to 2016, and 200% over the five-year period from
2012-2016<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(12)</font></SUP>. Morgan Stanley&#146;s TSR over 2016 ranked first among
global peers<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(13)</font></SUP> and outperformed the S&amp;P 500 Financials Index
return of 23% against a backdrop of improved market conditions in the latter
half of 2016. </FONT></P>
<DIV align=center>
<TABLE style="LINE-HEIGHT: 14pt; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="70%" border=0>

  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-top: #007bc4 1pt solid; border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: left; width: 100%; background-color: #e6e7e8; padding-right: 4pt; padding-left: 4pt"><B><FONT face=Arial size=1>Morgan
      Stanley and S&amp;P 500 Financials Index Total Shareholder Returns
      (TSR)</FONT></B><B><FONT face=Arial size=1 COLOR=#007bc4><SUP>(12)</SUP></FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="100%" bgColor=#e6e7e8>
      <P align=center><IMG src="ms3206591-def14a7x1x1.jpg" border=0></P></TD></TR></TABLE></DIV><BR>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Section 3.2 contains further details about
Company performance; see also Section 5 &#147;Notes to the Compensation Discussion
and Analysis.&#148;</FONT></P>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt">1.2 Framework for Compensation
Decisions and Performance Evaluation</FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>At the start of 2016, the CMDS Committee,
in consultation with its independent compensation consultant, established a
target range for 2016 CEO pay of $28 million or more for superior performance to
$10 million or less for performance substantially below expectations. This
target range is reviewed and set annually and serves as a guideline for the CMDS
Committee. To inform its decision-making with respect to the appropriate target
range, the CMDS Committee considers compensation information for peers as
described in Section 3.1 under &#147;Benchmarking Target CEO Pay.&#148;</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2> The 2016 pay
decision for the CEO was made by the CMDS Committee, in consultation with the
entire Board, based on the CMDS Committee&#146;s assessment of Mr. Gorman&#146;s strong
individual performance through Morgan Stanley&#146;s continued progress on the
long-term strategic objectives approved by the Board, Morgan Stanley&#146;s
improvement in financial performance driven by disciplined expense control, and
Morgan Stanley&#146;s shareholder returns. </FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>In its evaluation of the Company&#146;s and Mr.
Gorman&#146;s performance, the CMDS Committee also considered that the Company
received a conditional non-objection to the 2016 Capital Plan (requiring
resubmission)<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(5)</font> </SUP></FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>and, while ROE, ex
DVA<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(7)</font></SUP> and Operating ROE<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(10)</font></SUP> </FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>for 2016 were approximately 8%, continued focus is needed to achieve the
ROE Target of 9 &#150; 11%<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(7)</font></SUP>by
2017.</FONT></P>
<P align=right><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#B3B5B8>Morgan Stanley 2017 Proxy
Statement&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#007BC4>47</FONT></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial size=2><A href="#toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></B></p>
<P STYLE="text-align: left"><FONT face=Arial size=1 color=#B3B5B8>EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>As a result, the CMDS Committee determined
that Company and individual performance warranted a 2016 pay decision for Mr.
Gorman of $22.5 million, a 7% increase from Mr. Gorman&#146;s 2015 pay of $21
million. The CMDS Committee believes that this decision appropriately aligns Mr.
Gorman&#146;s 2016 pay with 2016 performance.</FONT></P>
<DIV align=center>
<TABLE style="LINE-HEIGHT: 14pt; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="70%" border=0>

  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD style="BORDER-TOP: #007bc4 1pt solid; BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=center width="27%" bgColor=#e6e7e8><B><FONT face=Arial size=1>MS CEO
      Compensation Range</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD noWrap style="text-align: center" width="1%" bgColor=#e6e7e8>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </TD>

      CEO Performance</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD noWrap style="text-align: center" width="1%" bgColor=#e6e7e8>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </TD>

  <TR>
    <TD noWrap style="text-align: center" width="100%" bgColor=#e6e7e8 colSpan=5><IMG src="ms3206591-def14a7x2x1.jpg" border=0></TD></TR></TABLE></DIV><BR>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The alignment of Mr. Gorman&#146;s pay with
Company performance can also be demonstrated over the longer-term by the fact
that over the 2014-2016 period, Mr. Gorman&#146;s realizable pay has increased by
approximately 19% and the Company&#146;s three-year TSR for the same period is
42%<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(14)</font></SUP>.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Section 3.2 contains more details about
individual NEO performance. </FONT></P>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt">1.3 Compensation Elements
</FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Pay in a given year is delivered in a
combination of fixed compensation (generally, base salary), cash bonus, deferred
cash, restricted stock units (RSUs), and a long-term incentive program (LTIP)
award in the form of performance stock units. A significant portion of pay is
deferred, awarded in equity, subject to future stock price performance and
cancellation and clawback and, in the case of LTIP awards, subject to future
achievement of specified financial goals over a three-year period.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Mr. Gorman&#146;s 2016 pay was delivered in a
combination of these compensation elements, as outlined below. The CMDS
Committee believes this approach to executive compensation is consistent with
shareholder alignment, executive motivation, best practices, and regulatory
principles. Sections 4.2 and 4.3 contain more detail about the elements of our
compensation program.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#007BC4>48&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#B3B5B8>Morgan Stanley 2017 Proxy Statement</FONT></P>

<P style="PADDING-LEFT: 6pt; TEXT-INDENT: -6pt" align=left><FONT face=Arial size=1 color=#007BC4><SUP>*</SUP></FONT><B><FONT face=Arial size=1> </FONT></B><FONT face=Arial size=1>$22.5 million is the amount the CMDS Committee awarded to the
CEO in early 2017 for 2016 performance. This amount differs from the SEC
required disclosure in the &#147;2016 Summary Compensation Table.&#148; </FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>With the exception of Mr. Rosenthal, who
did not receive an LTIP award in light of his ceasing to be a member of our
Operating Committee as of December 31, 2016, the NEOs received their 2016
compensation in the same elements as described in the chart above. Section 4.1
contains the 2016 compensation decisions for each NEO, which follow a similar
performance evaluation process.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt">1.4 Shareholder Engagement and &#147;Say on
Pay&#148; Vote</FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Morgan Stanley is committed to open and
ongoing communication with our shareholders, and takes the opportunity to engage
with shareholders directly on compensation and other matters to understand their
perspectives and provide information about Morgan Stanley&#146;s programs,
performance assessment, and decision-making process. </FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>A substantial majority (approximately 90%)
of the votes cast at the May 2016 annual meeting of shareholders were in favor
of our annual &#147;Say on Pay&#148; proposal. In 2016, we continued our engagement
program, seeking feedback from shareholders and proxy advisory firms on a
variety of topics, including executive compensation, corporate governance, and
environmental and social goals. The feedback that we received during the
engagement program was conveyed to the CMDS Committee and the Board.
Shareholders who provided feedback during our engagement program generally
reported that executive compensation at Morgan Stanley was viewed as
well-aligned with performance. The CMDS Committee factored shareholder feedback,
including the &#147;Say on Pay&#148; vote results, into its consideration of executive
compensation structure and determination of 2016 NEO pay levels. </FONT></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>After carefully considering shareholder
feedback, the CMDS Committee maintained its performance-based approach to
executive compensation, and executive pay increased for 2016 after evaluation
against strategic and financial objectives as well as shareholder returns.
</FONT></P>
<P align=right><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#B3B5B8>Morgan Stanley 2017 Proxy
Statement&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#007BC4>49</FONT></P>

  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 4pt; PADDING-LEFT: 4pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt; PADDING-TOP: 4pt" width="1%" bgColor=#e6e7e8></TD>

      <BR>Compensation <BR>with Shareholders&#146; <BR>Interests</FONT></B></P></TD>

      <DIV style="PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; TEXT-INDENT: -14.5pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><FONT style="PADDING-RIGHT: 8pt; FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" face=arial color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>Deliver a significant

      executive compensation directly to the Company&#146;s stock price and encourage
      ownership by requiring executives to retain shares</FONT></DIV>
      <DIV style="PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; TEXT-INDENT: -14.5pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><FONT style="PADDING-RIGHT: 8pt; FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" face=arial color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>Ongoing shareholder

      Decisions</FONT></B></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt">3.1 Factors Considered in Compensation
Decisions</FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The 2016 compensation of the NEOs was
determined by the CMDS Committee after consideration of Company business results
and strategic performance and individual performance, as well as competitor
compensation data and, with respect to the CEO, benchmarking data, and other
considerations set forth below.</FONT></P>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; TEXT-ALIGN: left" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%"><STRONG>Company and
      Individual Performance Review.</STRONG><FONT face=Arial size=2> To inform
      its decision-making process for NEO compensation for 2016, the CMDS
      Committee evaluated Company and individual performance. For 2016, a number
      of performance priorities were set by the CMDS Committee and the Board at
      the beginning of the year. The performance priorities are established
      based on a directional assessment made at the beginning of the year in
      light of the market environment and the Company&#146;s strategic objectives,
      and their attainment or non-attainment does not correspond to any specific
      compensation decision.</FONT></TD></TR>                                             <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top"></TD>

priorities in the following areas:</TD></TR>
