<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial size=2><A href="#toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></B></p>
<P STYLE="text-align: right"><FONT face=Arial size=1 color=#B3B5B8>EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION</FONT></P>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; TEXT-ALIGN: left" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%"><STRONG>Compensation Market Data.</STRONG><FONT face=Arial size=2> The Company uses a comparison group consisting of Bank of America
      Corp., Barclays Plc, Citigroup Inc., Credit Suisse Group, Deutsche Bank
      AG, Goldman Sachs Group Inc., JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co., UBS AG, and Wells
      Fargo &amp; Company (Comparison Group) to understand market practices and
      trends, evaluate the competitiveness of our compensation programs, and
      inform compensation decisions. Our Comparison Group consists of companies
      that either directly compete with us for business and/or talent or are
      global organizations with scope, size, or other characteristics similar to
      those of the Company. During 2016, the CMDS Committee reviewed analyses of
      our competitors&#146; pay levels, including historical compensation data
      obtained from public filings and compensation surveys conducted by
      consultants on an unattributed basis, as well as compensation plan
      design.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%"><STRONG>Benchmarking Target CEO Pay.</STRONG><FONT face=Arial size=2> As discussed in Section 1.2, the CMDS Committee, in consultation
      with its independent compensation consultant, established a target range
      for 2016 compensation for the CEO of $28 million or more for superior
      performance to $10 million or less for performance substantially below
      expectations. To inform its decision-making with respect to the
      appropriate target range, the CMDS Committee reviewed 2015 compensation
      levels for the 16 financial companies in the S&amp;P 100 (AIG, Allstate,
      American Express, BlackRock, Bank of New York Mellon, Capital One
      Financial, MasterCard, MetLife, Paypal, US Bancorp, VISA, and the five
      U.S. companies within the Comparison Group), which are intended to reflect
      institutions of similar size, scope, and complexity. The CMDS Committee
      then utilized the range of results as a benchmark from which to set the
      target range for 2016 compensation for the CEO.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%"><STRONG>Input and
      Recommendations from the CEO, Independent Directors and CMDS Committee&#146;s
      Independent Consultant.</STRONG><FONT face=Arial size=2> At the end of the
      year, Mr. Gorman presented the CMDS Committee with performance assessments
      and compensation recommendations for each NEO other than himself. The CMDS
      Committee reviewed these recommendations with the CMDS Committee&#146;s
      independent compensation consultant to assess whether they were reasonable
      compared with the market for executive talent and met in executive session
      to discuss the performance of our CEO and the other NEOs and to determine
      their compensation. In addition, the CMDS Committee reviewed proposed NEO
      incentive compensation with the entire Board (other than Mr. Gorman) in
      executive session.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%"><STRONG>Compensation Expense Considerations.</STRONG><FONT face=Arial size=2> Prior to determining individual NEO incentive
      compensation, the CMDS Committee reviewed and considered the relationship
      between Company performance, total compensation expense (which includes
      fixed compensation costs such as base salaries, allowances, benefits, and
      commissions), and incentive compensation as a subset of overall
      compensation expense. This exercise furthers the balancing of the
      objectives of delivering returns for shareholders and providing
      appropriate rewards to motivate superior individual
  performance.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%"><STRONG>Global
      Regulatory Principles.</STRONG><FONT face=Arial size=2> The Company&#146;s
      compensation practices are subject to oversight by our regulators in the
      U.S. and internationally. Throughout 2016, senior management briefed the
      CMDS Committee on relevant regulatory developments, including with regard
      to the mix of incentive compensation and the portion of compensation that
      should be deferred for certain populations, as well as principles of
      balanced risk-taking. For example, the Company is subject to the Federal
      Reserve Board&#146;s (Federal Reserve) guidance that is designed to help ensure
      that incentive compensation paid by banking organizations does not
      encourage imprudent risk-taking that threatens the organizations&#146; safety
      and soundness. The Company is also subject to the compensation-related
      provisions of the Dodd-Frank Act, as well as the remuneration code of the
      U.K. Financial Conduct Authority and the U.K. Prudential Regulation
      Authority Rulebook (Remuneration Part) (together, the U.K. Remuneration
      Code), which prescribes the compensation structure for certain employees
      who are identified as material risk takers (referred to as Code Staff
      employees).</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%"><STRONG>Relative
      Pay Considerations.</STRONG><FONT face=Arial size=2> We place importance
      on the pay relationships among members of our Operating Committee because
      we view our Operating Committee members as highly talented executives
      capable of rotating among the leadership positions of our businesses and
      key functions. Our goal is always to be in a position to appoint our most
      senior executives from within our Company and to incent our people to
      aspire to senior executive roles. At year-end, the CMDS Committee reviewed
      the relative differences between the compensation for the CEO and other
      NEOs and between the NEOs and other members of the Operating
      Committee.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top width="99%"><STRONG>Tax Deductibility.</STRONG><FONT face=Arial size=2> Section 162(m) of the Internal Revenue Code (Section
      162(m)) limits the tax deductibility of compensation for certain executive
      officers (other than the CFO) that is more than $1 million, unless the
      compensation qualifies as &#147;performance-based.&#148; To qualify as
      &#147;performance-based&#148; compensation, the award must be based on objective,
      pre-established performance criteria approved by shareholders or otherwise
      qualify as &#147;performance-based&#148; under Section 162(m). While our policy, in
      general, is to maximize the tax deductibility of compensation paid to
      executive officers covered under Section 162(m), the CMDS Committee
      nevertheless may authorize awards or payments that might not be tax
      deductible if it believes they are in the best interests of the Company
      and its shareholders.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P align=right><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#B3B5B8>Morgan Stanley 2017 Proxy
Statement&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#007BC4>51</FONT></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial size=2><A href="#toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></B></p>
<P STYLE="text-align: left"><FONT face=Arial size=1 color=#B3B5B8>EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION</FONT></P>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt">3.2 Evaluating Company and Individual
Performance for Alignment with Executive Compensation</FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>In determining the annual performance
compensation of the CEO and other NEOs, the CMDS Committee weighed the Company&#146;s
progress toward long-term strategic objectives, overall financial performance,
and, as applicable, business unit performance. Morgan Stanley&#146;s financial
performance continued to improve in 2016, and the Company entered 2017 well
positioned strategically and with strong capital and liquidity levels. The
strategic progress and improved financial performance were reflected in Morgan
Stanley&#146;s share price. Morgan Stanley&#146;s TSR<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(12)</font></SUP> was 36% for 2016,
outperforming the S&amp;P 500 Financials Index returns of 23%. PBT for 2016 grew
by 12% on flat revenues from 2015, ex DVA<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(8)(9)</font></SUP>. The Firm also
received a conditional non-objection from the Federal Reserve to its 2016
Capital Plan (requiring a resubmission)<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(5)</font> </SUP></FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>and, while ROE, ex DVA<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(7)</font></SUP> and Operating ROE<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(10)</font></SUP> for
2016 were approximately 8%, continued focus is needed to achieve the ROE Target
of 9 &#150; 11%<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(7)</font> </SUP></FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>by 2017. The CMDS
Committee considered these results, as well as the performance indicated below,
in determining compensation for our NEOs. </FONT></P>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; TEXT-ALIGN: left" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-bottom: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%"><STRONG>Strategic Objectives.</STRONG><FONT face=Arial size=2> During 2016, the Company achieved several milestones in
      connection with its overall strategy to continue to enhance shareholder
      returns:</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; TEXT-ALIGN: left" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">Significantly
      reduced non-compensation expense by $739 million, with the vast majority
      of these savings associated with our $1 billion expense reduction
      initiative, and maintained compensation expense discipline &#150; Institutional
      Securities compensation to net revenue ratio was 36%, achieving the target
      to be at or below 37%.</TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">Meaningful
      improvement in the Firm expense efficiency ratio, from 77.2% in 2015 ex
      DVA<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(11)</FONT></SUP> to 74.5% in 2016.</TD></TR>
    <TR>
<TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top"><FONT face=Arial size=2>PBT<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(8)</font></SUP> growth of $971 million
      (12% increase) on flat revenues from 2015 ex
  DVA<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(9)</font></SUP>.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">Achievement of #1
      ranking in Institutional Equities revenue wallet share for third
      consecutive year, gaining share in all three years (2014, 2015, and
      2016)<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(16)</font></SUP>.</TD></TR>
    <TR>
<TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top">Retained revenue footprint in Fixed Income with 25% headcount
      reduction and reduced resources.</TD></TR>
<TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">Achievement of #2
      ranking globally in Announced and Completed Mergers and Acquisitions,
      Initial Public Offerings, and Global Equity<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(17)</font></SUP>.</TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">Achieved Wealth
      Management pre-tax margin of 22%<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(4)</font></SUP> and record
      PBT<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(8)</font></SUP> of $3.4 billion, despite transactional revenue
    headwinds.</TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">Continued execution
      of U.S. Bank strategy in Wealth Management and Institutional Securities to
      support growth in net interest income and lending<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(18)</font></SUP>.</TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">TSR was 36% over
      2016, 42% over the three-year period from 2014 to 2016, and 200% over the
      five year period from 2012-2016<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(12)</FONT></SUP>.</TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">Increased the
      quarterly common stock dividend to $0.20 per share from $0.15 per share
      (+33% from 2015) and share repurchases of up to $3.5 billion (+40% from
      2015)<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(5)</font></SUP>.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; TEXT-ALIGN: left" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%"><STRONG>Company
      Financial Performance.</STRONG><FONT face=Arial size=2><SUP><font color=#007BC4>(1)(2)</font></SUP>
      Management reviewed the Company&#146;s forecasted 2016 financial performance
      with the CMDS Committee in December 2016, and the CMDS Committee assessed
      full-year actual financial results before finalizing compensation
      decisions in January 2017.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; TEXT-ALIGN: left" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%"><EM>Company-wide.</EM><FONT face=Arial size=2> Morgan Stanley
      reported improved financial performance in 2016 over 2015 excluding the
      impact of DVA. The Company reported net revenues of $34.6 billion and net
      income applicable to Morgan Stanley of $6.0 billion, or $2.92 per diluted
      common share for 2016. This compared with net revenues of $35.2 billion
      and net income applicable to Morgan Stanley of $6.1 billion, or $2.90 per
      diluted common share for 2015. Excluding the impact of DVA, 2015 revenues
      were $34.5 billion and net income applicable to Morgan Stanley was $5.7
      billion, or $2.70 per diluted common share<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(6)(19)</font></SUP>.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top width="99%"><EM>Institutional Securities.</EM><FONT face=Arial size=2> Institutional Securities reported PBT of $5.1 billion
      in 2016, compared with a PBT of $4.7 million in the prior year or $4.1
      billion excluding DVA<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(8)(20)</font></SUP>. Results were driven by strong
      performance across our Sales and Trading franchise, partially offset by
      lower revenues in Investment Banking. Non-interest expenses of $12.3
      billion in 2016 declined 7% from the prior year reflecting disciplined
      compensation management, lower litigation costs and expense
      management.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#007BC4>52&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#B3B5B8>Morgan Stanley 2017 Proxy Statement</FONT></P>

    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%"><FONT face=Arial size=2><EM>Wealth Management.</EM><FONT face=Arial size=2> Wealth
      Management reported PBT of $3.4 billion compared with $3.3 billion in the
      prior year, and a pre-tax margin of 22% flat to 2015<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(8)(4)</FONT></SUP>.
      Results reflect continued execution of our U.S. Bank<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(18)</FONT></SUP>
      deposit deployment strategy and positive fee based asset flows, with
      continued focus on expense discipline.</FONT></FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top style="PADDING-bottom: 4pt" width="99%"><FONT face=Arial size=2><EM>Investment
      Management.</EM><FONT face=Arial size=2> Investment Management reported
      PBT of $287 million in 2016 compared with $492 million in the prior
      year<SUP><font color=#007BC4>(8)</FONT></SUP>. These results reflect lower investment gains and
      carried interest revenue and losses on the disposal of legacy third-party
      sponsored funds, while asset management, distribution and administration
      fees were stable.</FONT></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>

      leadership of the Company, including: articulating and executing a
      Companywide long-term strategy to enhance profitability and returns to
      shareholders; contributing to improved financial performance in 2016

      agencies, shareholders, clients and the media. </TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>

      accordance with the Company&#146;s long-term strategy and execution of the U.S.
      Bank strategy; increased collaboration between the Institutional
      Securities and Wealth Management segments; and numerous interactions with
      employees, clients and regulators across many jurisdictions.</TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">Mr. Pruzan&#146;s leadership of Finance,
      including his efforts with respect to materially redesigning the capital
      management process to strengthen controls and governance around risk
      identification, scenario design, assumptions and models; the Firm&#146;s cost
      reduction efforts; execution of an efficient liquidity and funding program
      that accounts for evolving regulatory developments; strengthening the
      budget and planning process consistent with the Company&#146;s strategic
      objectives; developing and recruiting talent; and working closely with
      global and U.S. regulators, research analysts, rating agencies,
      shareholders, and clients.</TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%">Mr. Rosenthal&#146;s continued leadership of
      several support functions including Operations and Technology and Data,
      including increased focus on cybersecurity and innovative technologies to
      improve efficiency; advancing Wealth Management&#146;s digital strategy to
      provide tools to enhance the client experience and provide capabilities to
      attract a new customer base; and chairing of the Company&#146;s U.S. bank
      subsidiaries with a focus on profitable growth and heightened governance
      expectations.</TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 26pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9675;</FONT></TD>
    <TD  vAlign=top width="99%">Mr. Simkowitz&#146;s leadership of Investment
      Management, becoming an executive officer, and positioning the business
      for growth, including his efforts with respect to an organizational
      realignment aimed at unifying the business from both a managerial and
      product standpoint and rationalizing the cost base; disposal of legacy
      third-party sponsored funds; maintaining stable management fee revenue;
      deeply engaging with clients and strengthening coverage models globally;
      and launching new products and fundraising across a number of funds,
      including private infrastructure and real estate.

<P align=right><FONT face=Arial size=1><FONT color=#b3b5b8>EXECUTIVE
COMPENSATION</FONT></FONT></P>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt">4.2 Annual Compensation Program
Elements</FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The following chart provides a brief
summary of the principal elements of the Company&#146;s 2016 annual compensation
program for our NEOs. Each NEO receives a base salary and is eligible to receive
discretionary annual performance compensation for prior-year performance. Annual
performance compensation is intended to reward NEOs for achievement of the
Company&#146;s financial and strategic objectives over the prior year and is
delivered in a mix of a cash bonus, a deferred equity award, and a deferred
cash-based award. The LTIP awards, which are deferred equity awards that are
subject to future achievement of specified financial goals over a three-year
period, are described in Section 4.3 &#147;Long-Term Incentive Program.&#148;</FONT></P>
<TABLE style="LINE-HEIGHT: normal; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-top: #007bc4 1pt solid; border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: left; width: 22%; background-color: #ffffff; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt; padding-left: 4pt">&nbsp;</TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-top: #007bc4 1pt solid; border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: left; width: 1%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-top: #007bc4 1pt solid; border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: left; width: 35%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt"><B><FONT face=Arial size=1>Purpose</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-top: #007bc4 1pt solid; border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: left; width: 1%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-top: #007bc4 1pt solid; border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: left; width: 40%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt; padding-right: 4pt"><B><FONT face=Arial size=1>Features</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 22%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt; padding-left: 4pt"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>Base Salary<FONT color=#007bc4>*</FONT></FONT></B></TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 1%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt"></TD>
    <TD STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 35%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>Base salary reflects level of experience and
      responsibility and is intended to be competitive with salaries for
      comparable positions at competitors.</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 1%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt"></TD>
    <TD STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 40%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt; padding-right: 4pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>Base salaries are reviewed periodically and are subject
      to change for, among other reasons, a change in responsibilities or the
      competitive environment.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 22%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt; padding-left: 4pt"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>Cash Bonus</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 1%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt"></TD>
    <TD STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 35%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>Paying a portion of compensation in cash bonus is aligned
      with competitive pay approaches.</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 1%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt"></TD>
    <TD STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 40%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt; padding-right: 4pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>The portion of cash bonus is intended to be consistent
      with practice among the Comparison Group. Higher compensated employees
      continue to be subject to higher deferral levels.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 22%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt; padding-left: 4pt"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>Deferred Equity Award<BR>&ndash;&nbsp;RSUs</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 1%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt"></TD>
    <TD STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 35%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>Equity awards link realized value to shareholder returns,
      and the terms of the awards support retention objectives and mitigate
      excessive risk-taking over a three-year deferral period.</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 1%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt"></TD>
    <TD STYLE="vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 40%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt; padding-right: 4pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>Awards are subject to cancellation for competition, cause
      (i.e., any act or omission that constitutes a breach of obligation to the
      Company, including failure to comply with internal compliance, ethics or
      risk management standards, and failure or refusal to perform duties
      satisfactorily, including supervisory and management duties), disclosure
      of proprietary information, and solicitation of employees or
      clients.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 22%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt; padding-left: 4pt"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>Deferred Cash-Based<BR>Award&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;MSCIP</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 1%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt"></TD>
    <TD STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 35%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>The terms of deferred cash-based awards support retention
      objectives and mitigate excessive risk-taking. The awards provide a cash
      incentive with a rate of return based upon notional reference investments
      over a two-year deferral period.</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 1%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt"></TD>
    <TD STYLE="border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; vertical-align: top; text-align: left; width: 40%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 2pt; padding-right: 4pt"><FONT face=Arial size=2>Awards are subject to clawback if an employee&#146;s act or
      omission (including with respect to direct supervisory responsibilities)
      causes a restatement of the Company&#146;s consolidated financial results,
      constitutes a violation of the Company&#146;s global risk management
      principles, policies and standards, or causes a loss of revenue associated
      with a position on which the employee was paid and the employee operated
      outside of internal control policies. <BR><BR>Awards to Operating Committee
      members (including NEOs) are also subject to clawback if the CMDS
      Committee determines that the Operating Committee member had significant
      responsibility for a material adverse outcome for the Company or any of
      its businesses or functions.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>
<TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 3pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1><FONT color=#007bc4><SUP>*</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Mr. Kelleher was identified as a Code Staff employee
      under the U.K. Remuneration Code for the period January 1, 2016 to
      February 5, 2016 and, therefore, also received fixed compensation in the
      form of allowances based on his specific U.K. director and officer roles
      and responsibilities, pro-rated for the relevant period. Mr. Kelleher&#146;s
      prorated allowances were paid in cash in December
  2016.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P align=right><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#b3b5b8>Morgan Stanley 2017 Proxy
Statement&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT> <FONT face=Arial size=2><FONT color=#007bc4>55</FONT></FONT></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>

<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial size=2><A href="#toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></B></p>

<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=1><FONT color=#b3b5b8>EXECUTIVE
COMPENSATION</FONT></FONT></P>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt">4.3 Long-Term Incentive
Program</FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The 2017-2019 LTIP awards tie a meaningful
portion of each NEO&#146;s compensation to the Company&#146;s long-term financial
performance and reinforce the NEO&#146;s accountability for the achievement of the
Company&#146;s financial and strategic goals by directly linking the ultimate
realizable award value to prospective performance against core financial
measures over a three-year period.</FONT></P>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; TEXT-ALIGN: left" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%"><B><FONT face=Arial size=2>General Terms.</FONT></B> <FONT face=Arial size=2>The 2017-2019
      LTIP awards will vest and convert to shares of the Company&#146;s common stock
      at the end of the three-year performance period only if the Company
      achieves predetermined performance goals with respect to ROE and relative
      TSR, as set forth below, over the period beginning January 1, 2017 and
      ending December 31, 2019. While each participant was awarded a target
      number of performance stock units, the actual number of units earned could
      vary from zero, if performance goals are not met, to up to 1.5 times
      target, if performance goals are meaningfully exceeded. No participant
      will receive any portion of the LTIP award if the threshold performance
      goals are not met.</FONT>
      <P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2></FONT><FONT face=Arial size=2>The
      LTIP awards remain subject to cancellation upon certain events until they
      are converted to shares of Company common stock. If, after conversion of
      the LTIP awards, the CMDS Committee determines that the performance
      certified by the CMDS Committee was based on materially inaccurate
      financial statements, then the shares delivered will be subject to
      clawback by the Company.<BR>&nbsp; </FONT></P></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%"><STRONG>Performance
      Goals.</STRONG> <FONT face=Arial size=2>One-half of the target LTIP award
      is earned based on the Company&#146;s average ROE over the three-year
      performance period (MS Average ROE). The other half of the target LTIP
      award is earned based on the Company&#146;s TSR over the three-year period (MS
      TSR) relative to the TSR of the S&amp;P 500 Financials Index over the
      three-year period (Index Group TSR). The number of stock units ultimately
      earned will be determined by multiplying each half of the target award by
      a multiplier as follows:</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<BR>
<TABLE style="LINE-HEIGHT: 14pt; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="1%">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-TOP: #007bc4 1pt solid; BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=left width="27%"><FONT face=Arial size=1><STRONG>MS Average ROE</STRONG><FONT color=#007bc4><SUP>*</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-TOP: #007bc4 1pt solid; BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=right width="1%">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-TOP: #007bc4 1pt solid; BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=right width="24%"><B><FONT face=Arial size=1>Multiplier</FONT></B></TD>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="1%">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-TOP: #007bc4 1pt solid; BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=left width="24%"><FONT face=Arial size=1><STRONG>Relative TSR</STRONG><FONT color=#007bc4><SUP>**</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-TOP: #007bc4 1pt solid; BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=right width="1%">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-TOP: #007bc4 1pt solid; BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=right width="20%"><B><FONT face=Arial size=1>Multiplier</FONT></B></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="1%"></TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=left width="27%"><FONT face=Arial size=2>11.5% or more</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=right width="1%"></TD>

    <TD noWrap align=left width="1%">&nbsp;</TD>

    <TD style="BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=right width="20%"><FONT face=Arial size=2>1.00</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="1%"></TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=left width="27%"><FONT face=Arial size=2>5%</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=right width="1%"></TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=right width="24%"><FONT face=Arial size=2>0.50</FONT></TD>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="1%"></TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=left width="24%"><FONT face=Arial size=2>-50%</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=right width="1%"></TD>

    <TD noWrap align=left width="1%"></TD>

    <TD style="BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=right width="1%"></TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=right width="24%"><FONT face=Arial size=2>0.00</FONT></TD>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="1%"></TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=left width="24%"><FONT face=Arial size=2>Less
      than -50%</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=right width="1%"></TD>
    <TD style="BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid" noWrap align=right width="20%"><FONT face=Arial size=2>0.00</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>
<TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-bottom: 4pt">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>*</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>MS Average ROE, for this purpose, excludes (a) the
      impact of DVA, (b) certain gains or losses associated with the sale of
      specified businesses, (c) specified goodwill impairments, (d) certain
      gains or losses associated with specified legal settlements relating to
      business activities conducted prior to January 1, 2011, and (e) specified
      cumulative catch-up adjustments resulting from changes in, or application
      of a new, accounting rule that are not applied on a full retrospective
      basis. If MS Average ROE is between two of the thresholds noted in the
      table, the number of stock units earned will be determined by
      straight-line interpolation between the two thresholds.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD vAlign=top noWrap></TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>**</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-top: 2pt; padding-bottom: 0in"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Relative TSR is determined by subtracting the Index
      Group TSR from the MS TSR; however, if performance for the period is
      negative, the multiplier may not exceed 1.00. If Relative TSR is between
      two of the thresholds noted in the table, the number of stock units earned
      will be determined by straight-line interpolation between the two
      thresholds.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>As described in further detail in note 2
to the &#147;2016 Grants of Plan-Based Awards Table,&#148; each of our NEOs received an
LTIP award in 2016 on similar terms as described above. Additionally, as
described in note 3 to the &#147;2016 Option Exercises and Stock Vested Table,&#148; LTIP
awards granted in 2014 vested at 100.76% of target, based on performance over
the three-year performance period ended December 31, 2016.</FONT></P>
<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt">4.4 Additional Compensation and
Benefits Information</FONT></B></P>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; TEXT-ALIGN: left" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%"><STRONG>Clawback
      Policies and Procedures</STRONG><FONT face=Arial size=2>. The Company&#146;s
      independent control functions (the Internal Audit, Legal, Risk, Human
      Resources and Finance departments) take part in a formalized review
      process for identifying and evaluating situations occurring throughout the
      course of the year that could require clawback or cancellation of
      previously awarded compensation, as well as downward adjustments to
      current year compensation. Clawbacks of previously awarded compensation
      are reviewed quarterly with a committee of senior management (currently
      the CFO, CLO, CRO, Chief Human Resources Officer (CHRO), and Chief
      Compliance Officer) and reported to the CMDS Committee. In addition, the
      Global Incentive Compensation Discretion Policy, which was adopted by the
      CMDS Committee in 2011, sets forth standards for managers on the use of
      discretion when making annual compensation decisions and considerations
      for assessing risk management and outcomes. Further, in 2016, the Company
      instituted a review by control functions (led by the CLO and the CHRO) for
      certain senior risk takers as a component of the Firm&#146;s performance
      evaluation process. Senior risk takers are senior executives who are
      responsible for revenue generation and expense management, and generally
      include heads of businesses, product lines or business functions;
      region/country heads; and other Managing Directors in Sales &amp; Trading.
      Results of the senior risk taker review were reviewed by the CLO and CHRO,
      shared with senior business unit leaders, and considered in compensation
      decisions.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2><FONT color=#007bc4>56</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT> <FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#b3b5b8>Morgan Stanley 2017 Proxy Statement</FONT></P>

<P align=RIGHT><FONT face=Arial size=1><FONT color=#b3b5b8>EXECUTIVE
COMPENSATION</FONT></FONT></P>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; TEXT-ALIGN: left" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 99%"><STRONG>No
      Severance or Change-in-Control Tax Gross-Up Protection</STRONG><I><FONT face=Arial size=2>.</FONT></I> <FONT face=Arial size=2>NEOs are not
      contractually entitled to cash severance payments upon termination of
      employment or to any golden parachute excise tax protection upon a
      change-in-control of Morgan Stanley.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 99%"><STRONG>Health and
      Insurance Benefits</STRONG><I><FONT face=Arial size=2>.</FONT></I> <FONT face=Arial size=2>All NEOs are eligible to participate in
      Company-sponsored health and insurance benefit programs available in the
      relevant jurisdiction to similarly-situated employees. In the U.S., higher
      compensated employees pay more to participate in the Company&#146;s medical
      plan. NEOs are also eligible to participate in Morgan Stanley&#146;s Executive
      Health Program, under which each NEO is eligible to receive Company-funded
      access to a private primary care physician offering on-call services and
      an annual executive health care assessment. Upon retirement, NEOs are
      eligible for Company-paid retiree medical coverage for themselves and
      eligible dependents following any termination of
      employment.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="vertical-align: top; width: 99%; padding-bottom: 4pt"><STRONG>Pension and Retirement</STRONG><I><FONT face=Arial size=2>.</FONT></I> <FONT face=Arial size=2>Company-provided
      retirement benefits in the U.S. include a tax-qualified 401(k) plan
      (401(k) Plan) and a frozen tax-qualified pension plan (the Employees
      Retirement Plan (ERP)). Certain NEOs may also be eligible to participate
      in the Company&#146;s frozen Supplemental Executive Retirement and Excess Plan
      (SEREP). The SEREP, which was originally intended to compensate for the
      limitations imposed under the ERP and Internal Revenue Code, was amended
      in 2014 to cease further benefit accruals. No NEO is awarded with credited
      service in excess of his/her actual service under the ERP or the SEREP.
      Pension and retirement benefits provided to NEOs are discussed in further
      detail under the &#147;2016 Pension Benefits Table.&#148;</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD STYLE="padding-right: 5pt; padding-left: 15pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="padding-bottom: 4pt; vertical-align: top; width: 99%"><STRONG>Personal
      Benefits</STRONG><I><FONT face=Arial size=2>.</FONT></I> <FONT face=Arial size=2>The Company provides personal benefits to certain of the NEOs for
      competitive and security reasons. The Company&#146;s Board-approved policy
      authorizes the CEO to use the Company&#146;s aircraft. As of January 1, 2010,
      Mr. Gorman entered into a time-share agreement with the Company permitting
      him to reimburse the Company for the incremental cost of his personal use
      of the Company aircraft. On February 25, 2016, the CMDS Committee approved
      that Mr. Kelleher, in connection with his relocation from the U.K. to the
      U.S., would receive standard relocation benefits and continuation of a
      housing allowance. Personal benefits provided to NEOs are discussed in
      further detail under the &#147;2016 Summary Compensation
      Table.&#148;</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 5pt; PADDING-LEFT: 15pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT style="FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt" color=#007bc4>&#9679;</FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="99%"><STRONG>Share
      Usage</STRONG><I><FONT face=Arial size=2>.</FONT></I> <FONT face=Arial size=2>Morgan Stanley pays a significant portion of incentive compensation
      as deferred equity awards, which aligns the interests of the Company&#146;s
      employees with those of its shareholders. The Company strives to maximize
      employee and shareholder alignment through the use of deferred equity
      awards, while minimizing dilution. The Company has evaluated whether to
      return to shareholders to request approval of additional shares at the
      2017 annual meeting of shareholders and has determined to request an
      additional 50 million shares, which we expect would allow us to make
      grants under the EICP for approximately three years. The share repurchase
      program offsets the dilutive impact of these additional shares. Since
      Morgan Stanley re-initiated the share repurchase program in 2013, the
      Company has increased share repurchases each year - 12 million, 28
      million, 59 million, and 117 million shares from 2013 to 2016,
      respectively.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>
<TABLE style="LINE-HEIGHT: 14pt; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD style="BORDER-BOTTOM: #007bc4 1pt solid" noWrap align=left width="100%"><B><FONT face=Arial style="font-size: 11pt"><FONT color=#007bc4>5. Notes to the Compensation
      Discussion and Analysis</FONT></FONT></B></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>

of the Company&#146;s financial and operating performance described in this
CD&amp;A:</FONT></P>

  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(1)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>

      measures to the comparable GAAP figures is included in either the 2016
      Form 10-K or herein.</FONT></TD></TR>

  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(4)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="vertical-align: top; width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Pre-tax margin
      represents income (loss) from continuing operations before income taxes
      divided by net revenues. Pre-tax margin is a non-GAAP financial measure
      that the Firm considers a useful measure for us, investors and analysts to
      assess operating performance.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(5)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>

      received a conditional non-objection from the Federal Reserve to its 2016
      Capital Plan. Pursuant to the conditional non-objection, the Firm is able
      to execute the capital actions set forth in the 2016 Capital Plan, which
      include increasing our common dividend to $0.20 per share beginning in the
      third quarter of 2016 and executing share repurchases of $3.5 billion
      during the period July 1, 2016 through June 30, 2017. On December 29,
      2016, the Firm submitted an additional capital plan addressing weaknesses
      identified in the capital planning process. In March 2017, the Firm
      received a non-objection from the Federal Reserve to its 2016 resubmitted
      Capital Plan. The Firm received a non-objection from the Federal Reserve
      to its 2015 Capital Plan, which included share repurchases of $3,125
      million for the period April 1, 2015 through June 30, 2016 (for
      comparative purposes the percentage change of buyback is based on 80% of
      the total 2015 approval representing four of the five approved
      quarters).</FONT></TD></TR>

<P align=right><FONT face=Arial size=2 color=#b3b5b8>Morgan Stanley 2017 Proxy
Statement&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT> <FONT face=Arial size=2><FONT color=#007bc4>57</FONT></FONT></P>
<HR align=center width="100%" noShade SIZE=2>

<DIV style="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always"></DIV><BR>

<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial size=2><A href="#toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></B></p>

<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=1><FONT color=#b3b5b8>EXECUTIVE
COMPENSATION</FONT></FONT></P>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 7pt" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0>
    <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(6)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="vertical-align: top; width: 100%; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Debt valuation
      adjustment (DVA) represents the change in fair value resulting from the
      fluctuations in the Firm&#146;s credit spreads and other credit factors related
      to liabilities carried at fair value, primarily certain long-term and
      short-term borrowings. The Firm believes that most investors and analysts
      assess its operating performance exclusive of DVA. Effective January 1,
      2016, pursuant to new accounting guidance that the Firm adopted, gains and
      losses from DVA are presented in other comprehensive income (i.e., a
      component of common equity) as opposed to net revenues and net income.
      Prior to January 1, 2016, gains and losses from DVA are presented in
      trading revenues (i.e., a component of Net
Revenues).</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(7)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Return on average common equity,
      ex DVA represents consolidated net income applicable to Morgan Stanley
      less preferred dividends as a percentage of average common equity,
      adjusted for the impact of DVA (defined herein as ROE, ex DVA). ROE, ex
      DVA is a non-GAAP financial measure that the Firm considers useful for us,
      investors and analysts to assess operating performance. Effective January
      1, 2016, as a result of the adoption of the accounting guidance related to
      DVA, referenced in note (6) above, we have redefined the calculation of
      ROE, ex DVA to adjust for DVA only in the denominator. Prior to January 1,
      2016, for the calculation of ROE, ex DVA, DVA is adjusted in both the
      numerator and denominator. The Company&#146;s targeted return on average common
      equity (defined herein as ROE Target) is derived based on ROE, ex
      DVA.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(8)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Pre-tax profit represents income
      (loss) from continuing operations before income taxes (defined herein as
      PBT). PBT is a non-GAAP financial measure that we consider to be a useful
      measure for us, investors and analysts to access operating performance.
      The growth in PBT is calculated as the percentage increase of 2016 PBT
      ($8,848) over 2015 PBT, ex DVA ($7,877 million, which excludes the
      positive impact of $618 million from DVA).</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(9)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>2015 Net Revenues were $34,537
      million, excluding the positive impact of $618 million from DVA. Net
      Revenue, ex DVA is a non-GAAP financial measure the Company considers
      useful for investors and analysts to allow better comparability of period
      to period operating performance.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(10)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Return on average common equity,
      ex DVA and net discrete tax benefits represents ROE, ex DVA as adjusted to
      exclude the impacts of net discrete tax benefits recognized by the Company
      in both the numerator and denominator (defined herein as Operating ROE).
      Operating ROE is a non-GAAP financial measure that the Firm considers
      useful for us, investors and analysts to assess operating performance. The
      impact of net discrete tax benefits on ROE, ex DVA was 0.8% in 2015. Net
      discrete tax benefits in 2016 of $68 million had no significant impact on
      the ROE, ex DVA calculation (approximately 10 bps).</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(11)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Firm Expense Efficiency ratio
      represents total non-interest expenses as a percentage of Net Revenues (or
      in 2015, Net Revenues, ex DVA). For 2015, the Expense Efficiency ratio was
      calculated as non-interest expenses of $26,660 million, divided by Net
      Revenues of $34,537, which excludes the positive impact of $618 million
      from DVA. The Expense Efficiency ratio, ex DVA is a non-GAAP financial
      measure the Company considers a useful measure for us, investors and
      analysts to assess operating performance.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(12)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Total shareholder return
      represents the change in share price over a period of time plus the
      dividends paid during such period, expressed as a percentage of the share
      price at the beginning of such period (defined herein as
TSR).</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(13)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Global peers include: Goldman
      Sachs, JP Morgan Chase, Bank of America, Citigroup, Barclays, UBS Group,
      Deutsche Bank, and Credit Suisse. Source for Peer Companies:
      Bloomberg.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(14)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Over the 2014 to 2016 period, Mr.
      Gorman&#146;s realizable pay increased approximately 19% compared to his pay as
      reported in the Summary Compensation Table for the relevant years, and the
      Company&#146;s three-year total TSR for the same period is 42%. Realizable pay
      for this period was $78.5 million, while Summary Compensation Table
      compensation for this period was $65.8 million. Realizable pay reflects
      the current value of the sum of base salary, cash bonus, stock awards and
      option awards disclosed in the 2014, 2015, and 2016 proxy statements. For
      purposes of this calculation, equity awards were valued using the closing
      price of Morgan Stanley common stock on December 31, 2016,
      performance-vested awards were valued based on performance at
      target.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(15)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Compensation to pre-compensation
      PBT ratio represents compensation and benefits expense as a percentage of
      PBT, excluding compensation and benefits expense.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(16)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Institutional Equities revenue
      market share is based on the sum of the reported net revenues for the
      equity sales and trading businesses of Morgan Stanley and the companies
      within the Comparison Group (excluding Wells Fargo &amp; Company); where
      applicable, the reported net revenues exclude DVA. Equity sales and
      trading net revenues, ex DVA is a non-GAAP financial measure that the
      Company considers useful for investors and analysts to allow better
      comparability of period to period operating performance.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(17)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>The Company&#146;s capital markets
      rankings are reported by Thomson Reuters for the period of January 1, 2016
      to December 31, 2016.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(18)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>U.S. Bank refers to the Company&#146;s
      U.S. Bank operating subsidiaries Morgan Stanley Bank, N.A. and Morgan
      Stanley Private Bank, National Association, and excludes transactions with
      affiliated entities.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(19)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Company net revenues, ex DVA, net
      income applicable to Morgan Stanley, ex DVA, and earnings per diluted
      common share, ex DVA, are non-GAAP financial measures that the Company
      considers useful measures for investors to assess operating performance.
      For further information regarding these measures, see pages 34 and 36 of
      the 2016 Form 10-K.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(20)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Institutional Securities PBT, ex
      DVA excludes positive revenues from DVA of $618 million in 2015. PBT, ex
      DVA is a non-GAAP financial measure that the Company considers a useful
      measure for us, investors and analysts to assess operating
      performance.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>

<P align=left><B><FONT face=Arial style="font-size: 14pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><A NAME="p59"></A>COMPENSATION,
MANAGEMENT DEVELOPMENT AND SUCCESSION COMMITTEE REPORT</FONT></FONT></B></P>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>We, the Compensation, Management
Development and Succession Committee of the Board of Directors of Morgan
Stanley, have reviewed and discussed with management the Compensation Discussion
and Analysis contained in this proxy statement. Based on such review and
discussions, we have recommended to the Board that the Compensation Discussion
and Analysis be included in this proxy statement and incorporated by reference
into the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December 31,
2016 filed with the SEC.</FONT></P>

<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>The following tables summarize the
compensation of our NEOs in the format specified by the SEC.</FONT></P>

      Table</FONT></FONT></B></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>
<P align=left><FONT face=Arial size=2>Pursuant to SEC rules, the following table
is required to include for a particular year only those stock awards and option
awards granted <U>during</U> the year, rather than awards granted <U>after</U> year-end that
were awarded for performance in that year. Our annual equity awards relating to
performance in a year are made shortly after year-end. Therefore, compensation
in the table includes not only non-equity compensation awarded for services in
the applicable year but, in the case of stock awards granted in the years
reported in the table, compensation awarded for performance in prior years and
forward-looking performance-vested compensation. A summary of the CMDS
Committee&#146;s decisions on the compensation awarded to our NEOs for 2016
performance can be found in the CD&amp;A.</FONT></P>

    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>For 2016, consists of RSUs
      granted on January 20, 2016 for performance in 2015 and forward-looking
      2016 LTIP awards granted on January 20, 2016, the realizable value of
      which is dependent entirely on the satisfaction of predetermined
      performance goals over a three-year performance period. For further
      details on 2015 RSUs and 2016 LTIP awards, see &#147;2016 Grants of Plan-Based
      Awards Table.&#148;</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(4)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-top: 2pt">
      <P><FONT face=Arial size=1>Represents aggregate grant date fair value of
      awards granted during the applicable period for service during the prior
      year, as well as forward-looking performance-based compensation,
      determined in accordance with the applicable accounting guidance for
      equity-based awards.</FONT></P>
      <P><FONT face=Arial size=1>The following table lists the aggregate grant
      date fair value of stock unit awards granted to the NEOs during 2016. The
      aggregate grant date fair value of RSUs included in the table is based on
      the volume-weighted average price of the common stock on the grant date,
      and the aggregate grant date fair value of 2016 LTIP awards included in
      the table is based on the volume-weighted average price of the common
      stock on the grant date and the probable outcome of the performance
      conditions as of the grant date, in each case, as determined in accordance
      with applicable accounting guidance for equity-based awards. The value of
      the 2016 LTIP awards on the grant date, assuming that the highest level of
      performance conditions will be achieved, is $8,775,000 for Mr. Gorman;
      $4,932,598 for Mr. Kelleher; $2,459,178 for Mr. Pruzan; $3,000,000 for Mr.
      Rosenthal; and $2,939,754 for Mr.
Simkowitz.</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>

    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 4pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 2pt; WIDTH: 5%; PADDING-TOP: 2pt; BORDER-BOTTOM: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; TEXT-ALIGN: right" noWrap><FONT face=Arial size=2>&#151;</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>
<TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0 style="font-size: 7pt">

  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 3pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-left: 9pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(a)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>The &#147;2016 Change in Pension Value&#148; equals the
      aggregate increase from December 31, 2015 to December 31, 2016 in the
      actuarially determined present value of the accumulated benefit under the
      Company-sponsored defined benefit pension plans during the measurement
      period. Mr. Gorman, Mr. Pruzan and Mr. Simkowitz experienced an increase
      in the present value of their accumulated benefits from December 31, 2015
      to December 31, 2016 primarily due to a decrease in the discount rates
      described below and the plans&#146; adoption of a new mortality table. The
      present value of Mr. Kelleher&#146;s accumulated benefit increased from
      December 31, 2015 to December 31, 2016 due to a decrease in discount rates
      and the applicable exchange rate. The present values at December 31, 2016
      are based on the RP-2014 white collar mortality tables rolled back to 2006
      with projection Scale RP-2014 and then projected generationally with Scale
      MP-2016 and discount rates of 4.30% for the ERP and 4.02% for the SEREP.
      The present values at December 31, 2015 are based on RP-2014 mortality
      tables rolled back to 2006 with projection Scale RP-2014 and then
      projected generationally with Scale MP-2015 and discount rates of 4.49%
      for the ERP and 4.20% for the SEREP. Present values are determined using
      an interest-only discount before retirement. Post-retirement discounts are
      based on interest and mortality. For each plan, the assumed benefit
      commencement date is the earliest age at which the NEO can receive
      unreduced benefits under that plan or current age, if
greater.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 3pt; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-left: 9pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(b)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>Represents the difference between market interest rates
      determined pursuant to SEC rules and the earnings credited on deferred
      compensation.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0 style="font-size: 7pt">

  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP><FONT color=#007bc4><SUP>(6)</SUP></FONT></SUP></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>The &#147;All Other Compensation&#148; column for 2016 includes
      (a) contributions made by the Company under our defined contribution plans
      with respect to such period and (b) the incremental cost to the Company of
      perquisites and other personal benefits, as detailed below. In addition,
      our NEOs may participate on the same terms and conditions as other
      investors in investment funds that we may form and manage primarily for
      client investment, except that we may waive or lower applicable fees and
      charges for our employees.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>

  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt; padding-bottom: 4pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(1)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-bottom: 4pt; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>The 2016 LTIP awards included in this table are also
      disclosed in the &#147;Stock Awards&#148; column of the &#147;2016 Summary Compensation
      Table&#148; and the &#147;2016 Outstanding Equity Awards at Fiscal Year-End Table.&#148;
      The 2015 RSU awards included in this table are also disclosed in the
      &#147;Stock Awards&#148; column of the &#147;2016 Summary Compensation Table,&#148; the &#147;2016
      Option Exercises and Stock Vested Table&#148; and, other than Mr. Kelleher&#146;s
      Stock Bonus Award (described in note 3 below), the &#147;2016 Nonqualified
      Deferred Compensation Table.&#148; The 2016 LTIP awards and 2015 RSUs were
      granted under the Morgan Stanley Equity Incentive Compensation Plan. All
      2015 RSUs and 2016 LTIP awards are subject to cancellation if a
      cancellation event occurs at any time prior to the scheduled conversion
      date. For further details on cancellation and clawback of awards, see
      &#147;Potential Payments Upon Termination or Change-in-Control.&#148;</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="vertical-align: top; padding-right: 2pt"><FONT color=#007bc4><FONT face=Arial size=1><SUP>(2)</SUP></FONT></FONT></TD>
    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-top: 2pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>The 2016 LTIP awards are scheduled to vest and convert
      to shares in 2019 only if the Company satisfies predetermined performance
      goals over the three-year performance period consisting of 2016, 2017 and
      2018. One-half of the target 2016 LTIP award is earned based on the
      Company&#146;s average ROE over the three-year performance period (MS Average
      ROE). The other half of the target 2016 LTIP award is earned based on the
      Company&#146;s TSR over the three-year period (MS TSR) relative to the TSR of
      the S&amp;P 500 Financials Index over the three-year period (Index Group
      TSR). The number of stock units ultimately earned will be determined by
      multiplying each half of the target award by a multiplier as
      follows:</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>
<TABLE style="LINE-HEIGHT: 14pt; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR vAlign=bottom>
    <TD noWrap align=left width="1%">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
    <TD NOWRAP STYLE="border-top: #007bc4 1pt solid; border-bottom: #b3b5b8 1pt solid; text-align: left; width: 24%; padding-left: 4pt"><B><FONT face=Arial size=1>MS Average

    <TD STYLE="width: 100%; padding-top: 1pt"><FONT face=Arial size=1>MS Average ROE,
      for this purpose, excludes (a) the impact of DVA, (b) certain gains or
      losses associated with the sale of specified businesses, (c) specified
      goodwill impairments, (d) certain gains or losses associated with
      specified legal settlements relating to business activities conducted
      prior to January 1, 2011, and (e) specified cumulative catch-up
      adjustments resulting from changes in accounting principles that are not
      applied on a full retrospective basis. If MS Average ROE is between two of
      the thresholds noted in the table, the number of stock units earned will
      be determined by straight-line interpolation between the two
      thresholds.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>

<P align=right><FONT face=Arial size=1><FONT color=#b3b5b8>EXECUTIVE
COMPENSATION</FONT></FONT></P>
<TABLE style="FONT-SIZE: 8pt; FONT-FAMILY: Arial; BORDER-COLLAPSE: collapse; TEXT-ALIGN: left" cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0>

  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 2pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt;" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT color=#007bc4 size=1>**</FONT></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top width="98%" style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 6pt"><FONT size=1 face=Arial>Relative TSR will be
      determined by subtracting the Index Group TSR from the MS TSR. In no event
      may the multiplier exceed 1.0 if MS TSR for the performance period is
      negative. If Relative TSR is between two of the thresholds noted in the
      table, the number of stock units earned will be determined by
      straight-line interpolation between the two thresholds.</FONT></TD></TR>

  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 2pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT color=#007bc4 size=1></FONT></TD>
    <TD vAlign=top width="98%" style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt"><FONT size=1 face=Arial>Each NEO is
      entitled to receive cash dividend equivalents on the 2016 LTIP awards,
      subject to the same vesting, cancellation and payment provisions as the
      underlying award.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 2pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT color=#007bc4 size=1><SUP>(3)</SUP></FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt; PADDING-TOP: 2pt" vAlign=top width="99%" colSpan=2><FONT size=1 face=Arial>With the exception of Mr. Kelleher&#146;s awards, the
      RSUs are scheduled to convert to shares on January 28, 2019. Mr.
      Kelleher&#146;s RSUs are scheduled to convert to shares in three equal
      installments on each of January 18, 2017, January 22, 2018 and January 28,
      2019, except that 42,762 of Mr. Kelleher&#146;s RSUs (the Stock Bonus Award)
      plus reinvested dividend equivalents vested on July 20, 2016 and converted
      to shares on July 21, 2016, as prescribed by the U.K. Prudential
      Regulatory Authority. With the exception of Mr. Kelleher&#146;s Stock Bonus
      Award, the NEOs are retirement-eligible under the award terms at grant
      and, therefore, the awards are considered vested at grant for purposes of
      this proxy statement. The NEOs are entitled to receive dividend
      equivalents in the form of additional RSUs, subject to the same vesting,
      cancellation and payment provisions as the underlying RSUs.</FONT></TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD style="PADDING-RIGHT: 2pt; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4pt" vAlign=top width="1%"><FONT color=#007bc4 size=1><SUP>(4)</SUP></FONT></TD>
    <TD style="PADDING-TOP: 2pt" vAlign=top width="99%" colSpan=2><FONT size=1 face=Arial>Represents the aggregate grant date fair value, in accordance with
      the applicable accounting guidance for equity-based awards, of the RSUs
      and 2016 LTIP awards. The aggregate grant date fair value of the RSUs
      granted on January 20, 2016 is based on $25.1867, the volume-weighted
      average price of the common stock on the grant date. The aggregate grant
      date fair value of 2016 LTIP awards is based on the volume-weighted
      average price of the common stock on the grant date as well as the
      probable outcome of the performance conditions as of January 20, 2016. For
      further information on the valuation of the Company&#146;s RSUs and LTIP
      awards, see notes 2 and 18 to the consolidated financial statements
      included in the 2016 Form 10-K.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>

      accordance with SEC rules, the number of performance units reflected in
      the table represents the target number of units granted under the 2015
      LTIP award and the maximum number of units that may be earned under the
      2016 LTIP award. For both the 2015 and 2016 LTIP awards, the number of
      performance units reflected in the table exceeds the amount that would
      have been earned based on Company performance through December 31, 2016.
      Based on Company performance through December 31, 2016, 92.77% and 102.23%
      of the target number of units granted</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
